Post-conditions are Python functions that validate the output of an AI Function at runtime. If validation fails, the error message is fed back to the LLM for automatic retries. This ensures continuous verification, unlike traditional one-time human review. For example:
python
from ai_functions import PostConditionResult

def check_length(response):
    assert len(response) <= 50, f"Response too long, got {len(response)}"

@ai_function(post_conditions=[check_length])
def summarize(text: str) -> str:
    """Summarize the text in under 50 characters."""

AI Functions can be composed into multi-agent workflows by chaining calls between functions, where each function's output serves as input for another. For example:
python
@ai_function
def extract_emails(text: str) -> list[str]:
    """Extract all email addresses from the text."""

@ai_function
def generate_report(emails: list[str]) -> str:
    """Generate a report listing these emails."""

emails = extract_emails(text)
report = generate_report(emails)

This allows complex AI-driven workflows without manual code integration.
